Subsidy Traps
Cambridge, USA — No policy brings good economics into such direct conflict with good politics as food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming the core issue facing three of the world's most important new leaders: Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President "Jokowi" Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
Sisi's challenge of cutting subsidies is turning out to be better than expected.
In contrast, Modi is facing a worse situation than anticipated, which could even undermine the long-awaited WTO agreement.
While Jokowi's situation remains unclear.
In July, Sisi achieved something few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East have accomplished: he significantly cut long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41-78%.
Strangely, there were almost no opposition protests.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs over $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have remained so low that they are often used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often led to unrest, even toppling governments.
But the Sisi government seems to be making progress in this area as well.
Bread subsidies have already been cut by 13%.
Sisi had no choice.
Even after the subsidy cuts, the current government's target for the budget deficit for the next fiscal year reached 10% of GDP (it would have been 14% without the subsidy cuts).
However, almost no one expected Sisi, who came to power in a turbulent political environment, to act more swiftly than Modi, who, in India, where there was a strong desire for comprehensive economic reform, secured the prime ministership with an overwhelming democratic majority.
In Indonesia, Jokowi, who began his presidency in October, inherited long-standing fuel subsidies amounting to as much as $21 billion annually (20% of government spending), which had already burdened the country.
His predecessor, Susilo, had already taken a brave first step a year earlier by raising fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors recommended cutting the remaining subsidies, and he openly stated his plan to phase them out gradually over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies because agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive fields, it is the government — not large private monopolies — that is the root.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
Food and fossil fuel subsidies have sparked sharp controversy because they are often promoted under the banners of environmental protection or equality, but in reality they do little to achieve these goals and often have the opposite effect.
Less than 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies went to the poorest population, while 52.6% flowed into the pockets of the richest people.
Worldwide, far less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy, as evidenced by Modi's government, which aims to protect agricultural subsidies in India.
In fact, Modi's government's rejection of the WTO compromise ruined the most significant progress in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes benefit consumers at the expense of producers, especially in poor countries; and sometimes benefit producers at the expense of consumers, especially in rich countries.
India's policy aims to benefit both.
As a result, India has accomplished a feat: supplying wheat to consumers at artificially low prices, while simultaneously experiencing oversupply because farmers can get high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs — electricity, water, and fertilizers — while the environment is being damaged.
) The government has acquired large amounts of corrupt rice and wheat, and the small portion that reaches consumers is distributed in a corrupt manner that fails to achieve the goal of helping the poor.
The government may continue to provide subsidies and stockpurchases.
But it knows that this would violate WTO rules.
Since it is impossible to permanently change these rules, Modi simply rejected the WTO's eagerly awaited Trade Facilitation Agreement.
Once subsidies are implemented, they are hard to retract.
When world commodity prices rise (as they have over the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot shield them from the impact.
But people accustomed to government-set food and energy prices will demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a strong argument for not implementing subsidies from the very beginning.
However, this does not mean that once subsidies are in place, maintaining them is necessarily the best choice for shrewd politicians.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents could also erupt.
Similarly, if the growing gap eventually leads to even higher retail price increases, slow-moving leaders will not benefit either.
In an ideal scenario, while cutting food and energy subsidies, other more efficient measures to support low-income groups should be implemented.
Developing countries have already gained considerable experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as conditional cash transfer innovations like Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades and Brazil's Bolsa Família, as well as technological innovations like India's Unique Identification system.
But some countries are forced to adjust only when a budget crisis arrives, and they may not have the money available for transfer payments to alleviate the pain.
Smart politicians might should implement unpopular adjustments at the very beginning of their tenure.
Both Jokowi and Sisi have adopted this approach.
Modi, who won a major election victory under the banner of market reforms, is now falling behind.
